{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Since October 2004, more than half of children who did not have lawyers were deported, while only one in 10 children who had lawyers were sent back....", "abstract": "Children who are accused of violating United States immigration laws, civil offense, do not have right to legal representation in court; activists say situation has resulted in more than half of all children seeking asylum in United States ending up being deported; legal experts say American government is under no obligation to provide children who are not citizens with representation, but class-action lawsuit filed by ACLU and other civil rights organizations will attempt to address gap in laws.", "section_name": "U.S.", "print_page": "10", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Fernanda", "role": "reported", "lastname": "SANTOS", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By FERNANDA SANTOS"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/21/us/in-immigration-court-children-must-serve-as-their-own-lawyers.html", "lead_paragraph": "Since October 2004, more than half of children who did not have lawyers were deported, while only one in 10 children who had lawyers were sent back.", "headline": {"main": "It\u2019s Children Against Federal Lawyers in Immigration Court", "print_headline": "In Immigration Court, Children Must Serve as Own Lawyers"}, "_id": "57b8b8de95d0e021d7981c1f", "word_count": "1295", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/08/17/us/17unaccompanied1/17unaccompanied1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/08/17/us/17unaccompanied1/17unaccompanied1-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2016/08/17/us/17unaccompanied1/17unaccompanied1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/08/17/us/17unaccompanied1/17unaccompanied1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "400"}, "subtype": "x